1. Identify which seed matchups are most volatile
•	6 vs 11 (48.5%, 33/68)
•	8 vs 9 (48.5%, 33/68)
•	5 vs 12 (41.2%, 28/68)
•	7 vs 10 (40.3%, 27/67)
•	These matchups emphasize high unpredictability. With these matchups, it is essentially a coin flip in terms of predicting the correct outcome.
•	This can show why most “Cinderella” teams come from seeds 10-12.

2. Identify which rounds produce the most upsets
•	Elite Eight (44.1%, 30/68) 
o	Highest upset rate out of all rounds
•	Sweet Sixteen (33.1%, 45/136)
•	First Round (28.2%, 153/453)
o	Highest total number of upsets
•	The Elite Eight can be explained by having the highest upset rate because all the remaining teams have proved to be strong.

3. Discuss whether the tournament has become more/less predictable over time
•	Since 2008, the upset rate has varied between 17% and 35%, roughly. There is a slight upward trend from 2008 to 2024 of 0.04% per year. However, it is not statistically significant because the p-value is 0.883.
•	Recently, since 2024, the upset rate has dropped from 30% to 17% in 2025.
•	2025 has the lowest upset rate in 20 years.

